When we first started, we didn't just write one big pile of code. We used the segregation
method segregation, where we broke the project into small, separate pieces first. We gathered 
various ideas and tutorials from YouTube to help us understand how to structure a budget 
app, which we then used as the foundation for our logic. We made one piece for the colors 
and design, one piece for the math, and one piece for saving files. By working on these parts 
individually, we could make sure each one worked perfectly before we combined them into the 
final SmartSpend program. This made it much easier for us to find and fix mistakes because 
we knew exactly which section was responsible for each task.

For the look of the app, we used the Tkinter library to build the window and set it to a specific
size so it looks good on any screen. We used the tk.Label function to add titles and the tk.Entry
function to create boxes where the user can type their allowance and percentages. To keep things 
clean, we made a special function called create_input() that allowed us to build all the spending
boxes (like Food and School) using the same style. We also chose a "blue and white" color theme 
using hex codes like #e3f2fd to give the app a calm, professional feeling, inspired by modern UI 
designs we studied online.

We wanted to make sure our app was smart, so we added functions to handle how people type. 
We created a function called only_numbers that checks every keypress to make sure letters can't
be typed into the boxes. If someone tries to type a letter, the app simply won't let it appear.
We also added a Live Update feature using the .bind() function. This is really helpful because 
as soon as you release a key after typing a percentage, the app instantly calculates how much of
your 90% budget is left. This gives the user real-time feedback without them having to click a 
button every time.

The brain of our program is the calculate() function. When the user clicks the button, this 
function uses the .get() method to pull all the numbers from the entry boxes and turn them into 
decimals. We programmed it to automatically take 10% of the total allowance for savings first. 
Then, it takes the percentages for things like Toiletries or Misc and calculates the exact 
money amount using simple math (Allowance \times Percentage / 100). If there is any percentage 
left over from the 90%, we made the code smart enough to automatically move that extra money into 
an "Emergency Fund" so no 
cent is wasted.

To make the app feel more alive, we didn't just want the results to pop up instantly. We created a 
function called animate_text() that types out the budget list one letter at a time in the blue 
result box. Because the result list can get quite long, we needed a way to navigate it easily. We 
took a scroll bar template from Gemini and modified the code to fit our specific colors and layout. 
By integrating this template into our design, we created a smooth scrolling area that ensures the 
user can see their entire budget breakdown without the window becoming cluttered 
or messy. 

The last thing we added was a way to remember past budgets. We used the os and datetime modules to 
create a file on the computer called history.txt. Every time we hit calculate, the program opens 
this file and appends the new budget list along with the exact date and time. We also built a 
Show History button that opens a separate Toplevel window. This window reads the text file and 
displays everything we’ve ever calculated in a scrollable list. This final step ensures that 
SmartSpend isn't just a calculator, but a long-term tool for tracking how a student manages their 
money over time.

